The main challenge I encountered when training my agent was selecting appropriate hyperparameters. 
Choosing values for the learning rate, discount factor, and epsilon required trial and error, as different combinations led to very different learning outcomes. 
For example, when I used a higher learning rate, the agent learned faster initially but showed unstable performance across episodes. 
In contrast, a lower learning rate resulted in slower but more consistent improvement.

The discount factor also affected behavior. 
A higher discount factor encouraged the agent to prioritize long-term rewards, which improved performance in environments like FrozenLake where planning ahead is important. 
A lower discount factor caused the agent to focus more on immediate rewards, which sometimes led to suboptimal paths.

The exploration rate (epsilon) played a critical role as well. 
At higher epsilon values, the agent explored more, which helped it discover better strategies early in training. 
However, if epsilon remained high for too long, learning was inefficient. 
Gradually reducing epsilon over time helped the agent shift from exploration to exploitation and improved overall performance.

One real-world application of Q-Learning and reinforcement learning is in autonomous vehicles. 
RL can help vehicles learn optimal driving strategies by continuously interacting with their environment, improving safety, efficiency, and decision-making over time.
